# HELP_SECTION: ARCHITECTURE
ARCHITECTURE:

LPMP (lpmptool) is a log analysis tool that processes user-defined YAML
models to extract timing information from log files. Th tool searches log
files for the user defined patterns and analyzes time difference between
pattern matches to produce timing profiles.

Designed for KPI performance analysis, timing validation, and system
operation profiling across multiple domains' log files.

The tool operates through a pipeline architecture that
transforms patterns into host and system level timing profiles.

PROCESSING PIPELINE:
1. Model Loading     : Parse YAML model files with pattern definitions
2. Variable Expansion: Substitute {hostname} and custom variables in patterns
3. File Discovery    : Expand wildcards and locate log files
4. Pattern Matching  : Search logs using regex and literal string matching
5. Timestamp Parsing : Extract timestamps in multiple formats (sysinv, ISO)
6. Timing Analysis   : Calculate deltas and maintain chronological ordering
7. Output Generation : Produce tab-separated and CSV format results

CORE COMPONENTS:
• Command Line Interface : Argument parsing and configuration management
• YAML Model Loader      : Pattern definitions and settings validation
• Variable Substitution  : Dynamic pattern customization with {hostname}, {custom_var}
• Pattern Matching Engine: Regex and literal string matching with OR pattern support
• Timestamp Parser       : Multi-format timestamp extraction and validation
• File Position Tracker  : Chronological ordering maintenance across files
• Timing Analysis Engine : Delta calculation, tolerance handling, reordering logic
• Output Generator       : Dual format results (human-readable and CSV)

MODEL DESIGN PHILOSOPHY:
The YAML model system uses "blocks" as the fundamental unit of analysis. Each block
represents a specific event or operation to be timed, with automatic type detection
based on field presence. This design enables flexible modeling approaches from simple
event detection to complex multi-host collect bundle analysis.

PROCESSING MODES:
LPMP supports three distinct block types, each optimized for different analysis needs:

1. Pattern Blocks (Sequential Event Timing)
   - Use 'patterns:' field for sequential event timing
   - Patterns must be found in chronological order
   - Ideal for: Boot sequences, initialization chains, shutdown procedures
   - Performance: Stacking multiple patterns in a single block significantly improves
     performance by reducing file I/O overhead. Real-world testing shows 42% runtime
     reduction (31s → 18s for 5 loops) when consolidating 5 single-pattern blocks
     into one multi-pattern block. This optimization is most effective when patterns
     are found in the same log file and occur in chronological sequence.

2. Pair Blocks (Duration Measurement)
   - Use 'start:'/'stop:' fields for duration measurement
   - Measures precise time between start and stop events
   - Ideal for: Service startup timing, operation duration, performance analysis

3. Timeline Blocks (Event Collection)
   - Use 'timeline:' field for chronological event collection
   - Collects all matches regardless of order, sorts chronologically
   - Ideal for: Event correlation, maintenance timelines, multi-node bundle analysis

FILE HANDLING SYSTEM:
• Multi-file Support     : Search across multiple log files with fallback ordering
• Compression Support    : Transparent handling of .gz compressed files
• Wildcard Expansion     : Automatic pattern expansion (*.log, daemon.log*)
• Date-proximity Sorting : Files sorted by relevance to start_date
• Position Tracking      : Maintains chronological ordering within and across files
• Cross-platform Paths   : Works on Unix/Linux/macOS systems

MODEL FILE SEARCH PATH:
Model files are searched in priority order for maximum flexibility:
1. <tool_directory>/models/ - Highest priority (tool-relative)
2. ./models/ - Local development models
3. /etc/lpmp.d/ - User/developer models (writable in OSTree)
4. /var/lib/lpmp_models/ - System-provided models (read-only)
5. Explicit paths - Absolute or relative paths with separators

Note: The 'include' directive follows the same search path for modular model design.
