# HELP_SECTION: PROCESSING_AND_ANALYSIS
PROCESSING AND ANALYSIS:

LPMP provides comprehensive processing modes and analysis capabilities for different
log analysis scenarios, from single-host on-system analysis to multi-host collect
bundle correlation. On-system analysis is limited to the local host only; the tool
does not SSH to remote hosts.

PROCESSING MODES:
- Pattern Blocks: Sequential event timing with optional max_time_delta constraints
- Pair Blocks: Start/stop duration measurement with max_time_delta validation
- Timeline Blocks: Chronological event collection across all matches
- Mixed Models: Pattern and pair blocks freely interleaved for combined event timing

TIMING ANALYSIS:
- First match establishes baseline time (cumulative=0, delta=0)
- Subsequent matches calculate:
  * Cumulative time: seconds elapsed since first match
  * Delta time: seconds elapsed since previous match
- Time tolerance reordering handles out-of-order adjacent blocks
- Block-level and pair-level tolerance settings for flexible matching
- Chronological ordering maintained across files and hosts

LOOP ITERATION TIME ADVANCEMENT:
- When using multiple passes (loops > 1), the tool must advance the search start time
  after each pass to avoid finding the same patterns repeatedly.
- The tool advances by 500 milliseconds between iterations.
- This can cause issues when:
  - Log entries have timestamps with precision less than 500ms
  - Multiple relevant events occur within the same 500ms window
  - The tool may skip over valid patterns that fall within this advancement gap

WORKAROUND:
Use single-pass analysis (-n 1) when precise timing within 500ms windows is critical
Ensure log timestamps have sufficient precision (millisecond level recommended)
Design models with patterns that naturally progress beyond 500ms intervals

FILE HANDLING:
- Supports regular and gzipped (.gz) log files
- Wildcard expansion with date-proximity sorting
- Multi-file fallback search ordering
- Cross-platform path handling (Unix/Linux/macOS)

BUNDLE MODE (Multi-Host Analysis):
- Detects hosts from <hostname>_YYYYMMDD.HHMMSS directory structure
- Supports interactive (--hosts), include (--include), and exclude (--exclude) filtering
- Processes each host independently with per-host output directories
- Creates merged system profile from controller hosts only
- Output structure: lpmp_<lab>/<timestamp>_<model>/<hostname>/
- Automatic hostname variable substitution per host

BUNDLE MODE HOSTNAME OVERRIDE FEATURE:
- Block level 'override: <hostname>' for pattern search in override host logs dir
- Allows cross-host pattern matching within bundle mode
- Variables substituted using override hostname instead of current processing host
- Enables correlation analysis across multiple hosts in single model
- Example: Process controller-0 logs while also analyzing controller-1
           patterns in the same timeline. Profile Swact soak.
# END_HELP_SECTION: PROCESSING_AND_ANALYSIS

# HELP_SECTION: PATTERN_BLOCKS
PATTERN BLOCKS (Sequential Event Timing):

Pattern blocks search for patterns sequentially.
Each pattern must be found AFTER the previous pattern in the same block.
All patterns in a block must be found for the block to succeed.

BASIC SYNTAX:
blocks:
  - label: "System Boot"                  # Required: Description for output
    file: "kern.log"                      # Required: Log file(s) to search
    patterns:                             # Required: Sequential patterns list
      - "Kernel command line:"
    profile: true                         # Optional: Write per-block profile file (default: false)
    max_time_delta: 300                   # Optional: Max seconds between sequential patterns

MULTIPLE SEQUENTIAL PATTERNS:
blocks:
  - label: "System Initialization"
    file: "daemon.log*"
    patterns:
      - "Starting system initialization"   # Pattern 1 (must be found first)
      - "Loading kernel modules"           # Pattern 2 (must be found after pattern 1)
      - "System initialization complete"   # Pattern 3 (must be found after pattern 2)
    max_time_delta: 60                    # Allow up to 1 minute between sequential patterns

OR PATTERNS (Alternative Matches):
blocks:
  - label: "System Shutdown"
    file: ["daemon.log.1.gz", "daemon.log"] # Multiple files, searched in order
    optional: true                          # Skip if patterns not found
    patterns:
      - ["SIGTERM", "SIGINT"]               # OR patterns - first match wins
      - "Shutdown complete"                 # Sequential pattern after OR match

VARIABLE SUBSTITUTION AND REGEX:
blocks:
  - label: "Host State Change"
    file: "mtcAgent.log*"                   # Wildcard file pattern
    patterns:
      - "{hostname} Unlock Action"          # Variable substitution
      - r"{hostname} is (ENABLED|DEGRADED)" # Regex pattern with variable

KEY FEATURES:
• Sequential processing: Patterns must be found in order
• OR patterns: Use ["option1", "option2"] for alternatives
• Variable substitution: Use {hostname} and custom variables
• Full regex support: Use r"pattern" for regular expressions
• File position tracking: Maintains chronological ordering
• Optional blocks: Set optional: true to skip if patterns not found
• Profile files: Set profile: true for per-block timing files
• Timing constraints: Use max_time_delta for sequential pattern timing
# END_HELP_SECTION: PATTERN_BLOCKS

# HELP_SECTION: PAIR_BLOCKS
PAIR BLOCKS (Duration Measurement):

Pair blocks measure the time between start and stop patterns.
They are designed for timing operations that have clear beginning and end events.

BASIC SYNTAX:
blocks:
  - label: "Service Startup"             # Required: Description for output
    file: "service.log*"                 # Required: Log file(s) to search
    start: "Service starting"            # Required: Start pattern
    stop: "Service ready"                # Required: Stop pattern
    max_time_delta: 30                   # Optional: Block-specific max seconds between start->stop

REGEX PATTERNS:
blocks:
  - label: "Service Disable"
    file: "sm.log*"                      # Wildcard file patterns supported
    optional: true                       # Override required default
    start: r'Started.*for service \\(my-service\\)'                         # Regex start
    stop: r'Action \\(disable\\) completed.*for service \\(my-service\\)'  # Regex stop
    max_time_delta: 45                   # Custom timeout for this block

OUTPUT FORMAT:
Pair blocks generate detailed timing information:
  Delta(HH:MM:SS)  Hostname      Block Label       Log File  Data
  ---------------  ------------  ----------------  --------  --------
  00:00:01.5       controller-0  cert-alarm        sm.log    2026-02-18T11:59:18.570: Start -> Stop: 2026-02-18T11:59:20.105:   1.5s  # noqa E501
  00:00:01.3       controller-0  device-image-fs   sm.log    2026-02-18T11:59:20.105: Start -> Stop: 2026-02-18T11:59:21.417:   1.3s  # noqa E501

TIMING CONSTRAINTS:
• max_time_delta: Maximum seconds between start and stop patterns
• Block-level setting overrides model-level setting
• Prevents false matches from unrelated events
• Default: 45 seconds (configurable)

KEY FEATURES:
• Duration measurement: Calculates precise timing between start/stop events
• Timing validation: Enforces max_time_delta constraints
• Chronological ordering: Start pattern must occur before stop pattern
• Full regex support: Both start and stop patterns support regular expressions
• Variable substitution: Use {hostname} and custom variables in patterns
• Optional blocks: Set optional: true to skip if patterns not found
• Profile files: Set profile: true for per-block timing files with statistics
# END_HELP_SECTION: PAIR_BLOCKS

# HELP_SECTION: TIMELINE_BLOCKS
TIMELINE BLOCKS (Event Timeline):

Timeline blocks collect ALL matches for ALL specified patterns and
sort them chronologically.
Unlike pattern blocks, timeline blocks search independently for each
pattern with no order requirements.

NAMED PATTERN REFERENCE:
blocks:
  - label: "Maintenance Timeline"         # Required: Description for output
    file: "mtcAgent*"                     # Required: Log file(s) to search
    timeline: "{maintenance}"             # Required: Named pattern reference

# Named patterns defined in settings:
settings:
  timeline_patterns:
    maintenance:
      - "Host Add Completed"
      - "*** Heartbeat Miss ***"
      - "critical enable failure"
    network:
      - "Link Down"
      - "Link Up"
      - "Interface Error"

DIRECT PATTERN LIST:
blocks:
  - label: "Direct Timeline"              # Timeline with direct patterns
    file: "system.log"
    timeline:                             # Direct list of patterns
      - "System started"
      - "Service ready"
      - "System shutdown"
    optional: true

OUTPUT FORMAT:
Timeline blocks generate chronologically ordered events:
  Delta(HH:MM:SS)  Block Label       Log File      Data
  ---------------  ---------------   ------------  --------
  00:00:00.000     Maintenance       mtcAgent.log  <log line with matched pattern>
  00:00:15.234     Maintenance       mtcAgent.log  <log line with different pattern>
  00:00:17.333     Maintenance       mtcAgent.log  <log line chronologically ordered>

KEY FEATURES:
• Chronological collection: All matches collected and sorted by timestamp
• No order requirements: Patterns can be found in any order
• Named pattern sets: Reusable pattern definitions in settings
• Direct pattern lists: Patterns can be defined directly in the block
• Variable substitution: Full support for {hostname} and custom variables
• Full regex support: All patterns support regular expressions
• Multi-file support: Search across multiple log files with wildcards
• No timing constraints: max_time_delta does not apply to timeline blocks
• Profile files: Set profile: true for per-block timing files

USE CASES:
• Event correlation across multiple log sources
• Maintenance event sequencing and analysis
• Multi-controller event timeline generation
• Chronological analysis of events across all nodes in a collect bundle
# END_HELP_SECTION: TIMELINE_BLOCKS

# HELP_SECTION: WINDOW_BLOCKS
WINDOW BLOCKS (Time-Range Log Extraction):

Window blocks collect ALL timestamped log lines from matching files
within a time window. No pattern matching — pure time-range extraction.
This is a timeline variant activated by setting window: true.

BASIC SYNTAX:
blocks:
  - label: "All Logs"                    # Required: Description for output
    file: "*.log*"                       # Required: Log file(s) to search
    window: true                         # Required: Enables time-range extraction

MULTIPLE FILE PATTERNS:
blocks:
  - label: "Mtce Logs"
    file: ["mtcAgent.log*", "hbsAgent.log*", "pmond.log*"]
    window: true

  - label: "SM Logs"
    file: "sm.log*"
    window: true

WITH TIME BOUNDS IN SETTINGS:
settings:
  start_date: "2026-01-06T19:00:00"     # Optional, overridden by -s
  stop_date: "2026-01-06T20:00:00"      # Optional, overridden by -e

blocks:
  - label: "All Logs"
    file: "*.log*"
    window: true

TIME BOUND PRECEDENCE:
1. Command line -s / -e (highest)
2. Model settings start_date / stop_date
3. Auto-detected: 5 minutes before latest log timestamp

FILE FILTERING:
• Binary files skipped automatically (null bytes detected)
• Known non-log files skipped (wtmp, btmp, lastlog, *.db, etc.)
• Files with no parseable timestamps skipped
• Files outside time window skipped
• Files and directories in file_ignore_list_and_format_handling.yaml skipped
• Subdirectories searched recursively for log files
• Custom timestamp formats supported via file_ignore_list_and_format_handling.yaml

