# HELP_SECTION: MIXED_MODE_EXAMPLE
CREATING A MIXED MODE EXAMPLE COMBINING PATTERN AND PAIR BLOCKS FOR COMPREHENSIVE SYSTEM ANALYSIS:

This example demonstrates a comprehensive system analysis model that combines pattern blocks
for event detection and pair blocks for duration measurement, providing both event timing and
performance metrics. Pattern and pair blocks can be freely interleaved.

# Complete mixed mode model: system_analysis.yaml
settings:
  max_time_delta: 120           # Allow up to 2 minutes between patterns
  block_time_tolerance: 5.0     # Allow 5 second tolerance for block reordering
  max_log_length: 200           # Longer log lines for detailed analysis
  profile: true                 # Enable per-block profile files

blocks:
  # Pattern block: System boot anchor
  - label: "System Boot Trigger"
    file: "kern.log*"
    patterns:
      - "Kernel command line:"
    profile: true

  # Pair block: Service startup timing
  - label: "Critical Service Startup"
    file: "sm.log*"
    start: r"Started.*service \\(critical-service\\)"
    stop: r"Action \\(enable\\) completed.*service \\(critical-service\\)"
    max_time_delta: 60           # Override global setting for this block
    profile: true

  # Pattern block: Network initialization
  - label: "Network Interface Ready"
    file: "daemon.log*"
    patterns:
      - ["network interface up", "interface ready", "link established"]
    optional: true               # Network timing may vary

  # Pair block: Database initialization timing
  - label: "Database Initialization"
    file: "postgres.log*"
    start: "database system is starting up"
    stop: "database system is ready to accept connections"
    max_time_delta: 180          # Database may take longer
    profile: true

  # Pattern block: Application readiness
  - label: "Application Ready"
    file: "app.log*"
    patterns:
      - "Application initialized"
      - ["Ready to serve requests", "Server listening", "Service available"]

  # Pair block: Health check timing
  - label: "Health Check Cycle"
    file: "health.log*"
    start: "Starting health check"
    stop: "Health check completed"
    max_time_delta: 30           # Health checks should be fast
    optional: true               # May not always be present

KEY FEATURES DEMONSTRATED:
• Mixed block types: Combines pattern blocks (event detection) with pair blocks (duration measurement) in any order
• Sequential processing: Pattern blocks establish timing baseline, pair blocks measure durations
• Flexible timing: Different max_time_delta values for different operations
• Error handling: Optional blocks for non-critical components
• Performance profiling: Per-block profile files enabled for detailed analysis
• Regex patterns: Complex service matching with escaped parentheses
• OR patterns: Alternative success indicators for robust matching
• Wildcard files: Automatic log rotation handling

EXPECTED OUTPUT FORMAT:
Delta(HH:MM:SS)  Block Label               Log File      Data
---------------  -------------------------  ------------ --------
00:00:00.000     System Boot Trigger       kern.log     2024-01-06T10:15:20.100: Kernel command line: ...
00:00:05.234     Critical Service Startup  sm.log       10:15:20.100: Start -> Stop: 10:15:25.334: 5.234s
00:00:07.891     Network Interface Ready   daemon.log   2024-01-06T10:15:27.991: network interface up
00:00:12.456     Database Initialization   postgres.log 10:15:25.334: Start -> Stop: 10:15:37.790: 12.456s
00:00:15.123     Application Ready         app.log      2024-01-06T10:15:35.223: Application initialized
00:00:17.890     Application Ready         app.log      2024-01-06T10:15:37.990: Ready to serve requests
00:00:20.345     Health Check Cycle        health.log   10:15:37.790: Start -> Stop: 10:15:40.135: 2.345s

USAGE EXAMPLES:
# Basic mixed mode analysis
lpmptool -l /var/log -m system_analysis.yaml -o ./analysis_results

# With custom timing constraints
lpmptool -l /var/log -m system_analysis.yaml --max-time-delta 180 --block-time-tolerance 10.0

# Bundle mode for multi-host analysis
