# HELP_SECTION: LIMITATIONS
LIMITATIONS:

The Log Pattern Matching Profiler has the following known limitations:

1. SAME-TIMESTAMP PATTERN REPETITION:
   When multiple patterns exist at the exact same timestamp in the same log file,
   the tool may find the same pattern repeatedly across loop iterations (-n > 1).
   This occurs because the tool uses timestamp-based search advancement and cannot
   distinguish between patterns that share identical timestamps.

   WORKAROUND:
   - Use -n 1 (single pass) for models with same-timestamp patterns
   - Design models with patterns that naturally progress chronologically
   - Add blocks with longer time intervals to ensure timestamp progression

   TECHNICAL DETAILS:
   - The tool advances search time by 1 millisecond after each loop
   - If log timestamps only have millisecond precision and multiple patterns
     exist within the same millisecond, the search may not advance properly
   - This limitation affects pattern and pair blocks; timeline blocks are unaffected

2. COMPRESSED FILE POSITION TRACKING:
   File position tracking is not available for compressed (.gz) files.
   The tool relies on timestamp-based search progression for all file types.

3. CROSS-FILE PAIR BLOCK COORDINATION:
   Pair blocks spanning multiple files depend on timestamp synchronization
   between log files. Clock skew or logging delays may affect accuracy.

4. MEMORY USAGE:
   Large log files or high loop counts may consume significant memory,
   especially when processing multiple hosts in bundle mode.

5. REGEX PERFORMANCE:
   Complex regular expressions may impact performance on large log files.
   The tool falls back to literal string matching if regex compilation fails.

For questions or to report issues, consult the tool documentation or
contact the development team.
# END_HELP_SECTION: LIMITATIONS

5.  INCLUDE SETTINGS:
    - include: "filename.yaml" at top level
    - included files contribute only 'settings' (especially timeline_patterns)
    - include files follow the same search path as model files:
      * Explicit paths (absolute or relative with separator) have highest priority
      * Then searches: ./models/, /etc/lpmp.d/, /var/lib/lpmp_models/, ./
    - model-local settings override included settings by key

KEY FEATURES:
• Multi-file Support: Search across multiple log files with fallback ordering
• Compressed File Support: Handles both regular and gzipped (.gz) log files
• Chronological Ordering: Maintains temporal sequence across file searches
• Flexible Pattern Matching: Supports single patterns and OR pattern groups
• Multiple Timestamp Formats: Parses sysinv and ISO timestamp formats
• Configurable Loops: Run analysis multiple times or until EOF
• Time Filtering: Start analysis from specific timestamps
• Output Customization: Configurable log line truncation and dual format output
• Error Handling: Graceful failure with clear error messages
• Multi-Level Verbosity: 5 levels of debug output (-v to -vvvvv)
• Position Tracking: Ensures chronological ordering within and across files
• Dual Output: Tab-separated (.timing) and CSV (.csv) formats
• Timeline Mode: Chronological event analysis across multiple log sources
• Named Pattern Sets: Reusable pattern definitions for timeline blocks
• Pair Mode: Measure time between start/stop pattern pairs
• Regex Support: Full regular expression pattern matching
• Time Delta Validation: Configurable max_time_delta at model and block level
• Per-Block Profile Files: Optional per-block timing files with summary headers
• Test Head: Automated testing of features, failure detection and edge cases

TIMESTAMP FORMATS SUPPORTED:
• sysinv format: "sysinv 2024-01-06 12:30:45.123 message"
• ISO format   : "2024-01-06T12:30:45.123 message"

USAGE:
    python lpmptool --logs-dir /path/to/logs --model-file model.yaml
    python lpmptool -l var/log -m timing.yaml -o ./results -v
    python lpmptool --start-date "2024-01-06T10:00:00" --loops 0 -vv
    python lpmptool --max-time-delta 60 -m model.yaml  # Override timing constraints
    python lpmptool -b /path/to/bundle -l var/log --lab mylab -m model.yaml
    python lpmptool -m mixed_model.yaml -vvv  # Mixed pattern, pair and timeline blocks
    python lpmptool -m model.yaml -vvvvv      # Full debug output
    python lpmptool -m model.yaml --stats     # Enable memory usage monitoring

BUNDLE MODE:
    Bundle mode enables processing logs from multiple hosts in a collect bundle.

    DIRECTORY STRUCTURE:
    <bundle_dir>/
    ├── controller-0_20251218.082339/
    │   └── var/log/
    ├── controller-1_20251218.082339/
    │   └── var/log/
    └── worker-0_20251218.082339/
        └── var/log/

    REQUIREMENTS:
    • Host directories must follow format: <hostname>_YYYYMMDD.HHMMSS
    • All host dirs names must have the same date
    • Tool iterates over all detected hosts automatically


    HOST SELECTION:
    • --hosts: Interactive mode with prompts
    • --include: Process only specified hosts (non-interactive)
    • --exclude: Process all except specified hosts (non-interactive)
    • Options are mutually exclusive
    • All host names are validated against detected bundle hosts

    USAGE: (mutually exclusive)
    python lpmptool -b /path/to/bundle -l var/log -m model.yaml

    Filter: in or out Hosts
    python lpmptool -b /path/to/bundle --include controller-0 -m model.yaml
    python lpmptool -b /path/to/bundle --exclude worker-10 worker-11 -m model.yaml

    Go Interactive:
    python lpmptool -b /path/to/bundle --hosts -m model.yaml

    OUTPUT FILES:
    profile.timing              Main timing results (tab-separated, mirrors console output)
    profile.timing.csv          CSV format results
