MODEL FILE FORMAT (YAML):

    # PATTERN BLOCKS (Sequential Event Timing):
    # ----------------
    blocks:
      # Simple single pattern block
      - label: "Kernel Boot"
        file: "kern.log*"                     # Single file
        profile: true                        # Write per-block profile file
        patterns:
          - "Kernel command line:"           # Single pattern


      # Multiple sequential patterns in one block
      - label: "System Initialization"
        file: "daemon.log*"
        max_time_delta: 60                    # Allow up to 1 minute between sequential patterns
        patterns:
          - "Starting system initialization"  # Pattern 1 (must be found first)
          - "Loading kernel modules"          # Pattern 2 (must be found after pattern 1)
          - "System initialization complete"  # Pattern 3 (must be found after pattern 2)

      # OR patterns using array syntax
      - label: "System Shutdown"
        file: ["daemon.log.1.gz", "daemon.log"] # Multiple files, searched in order
        optional: true                          # Skip if patterns not found
        patterns:
          - ["SIGTERM", "SIGINT"]               # OR patterns - first match wins
          - "Shutdown complete"                 # Sequential pattern after OR match

      # Complex pattern block with variable substitution and regex
      - label: "Host State Change"
        file: "mtcAgent.log*"                   # Wildcard file pattern
        profile: true
        patterns:
          - "{hostname} Unlock Action"          # Variable substitution
          - r"{hostname} is (ENABLED|DEGRADED)" # Regex pattern with variable


      # Multi-file pattern block with fallback
      - label: "Service Status"
        file: ["service.log", "service.log.1.gz", "syslog"] # Try files in order
        patterns:
          - ["Service ready", "Service active"] # OR pattern for completion

    # PAIR BLOCKS:
    # ----------------
    blocks:
      - label: Simple Pair Block
        file: "sm.log*"                      # specify file with wildcard (includes rotation)
        max_time_delta: 30                   # Block-specific max seconds between start->stop
        - start: "Service starting"          # Start pattern
        - stop: "Service ready"              # Stop pattern

      - label: "Service Disable"             # with regex support
        file: ["sm.log*"]                    # Wildcard file patterns   # supported
        optional: true                       # override required default
        start: r'Started*for service \\(my-service\\)'                         # Regex start
        stop: r'Action \\(disable\\) completed.*for service \\(my-service\\)'  # Regex stop

    # TIMELINE BLOCKS:
    # ----------------
    blocks:
      - label: "Maintenance Events"
        file: ["mtcAgent*"]                  # Wildcard file patterns
        timeline: "{maintenance}"            # included named pattern reference
        optional: false                      # Requiredt for first match

      - label: "Direct Timeline"
        file: "system.log"
        timeline:                            # Direct pattern list
          - "System started"
          - "Service ready"
          - "System shutdown"
        optional: true

    # MIXED MODEL (Pattern + Pair blocks):
    # ------------------------------------
    blocks:
      - label: "Boot Trigger"               # Pattern block
        file: "kern.log"
        patterns:
          - "Kernel Command line:"

      - label: "Service Timing"            # Pair block
        file: "sm.log*"
        start: "Service starting"
        stop: "Service ready"

    # Optional global settings - blocks or command line can override
    # --------------------------------------------------------------
    settings:
      start_date: "2026-01-06T20:00:00"         # Start analysis from this timestamp
      loops: 3                                  # Number of passes (0=until EOF)
      max_log_length: 180                       # Truncate long log lines in output
      max_time_delta: {DEFAULT_MAX_TIME_DELTA}  # See MAX_TIME_DELTA CONFIGURATION section
                                                # - start->stop (pair blocks)
                                                # - sequential patterns (pattern blocks, when specified)
                                                # - not applicable to timeline blocks
      block_time_tolerance: 5.0                 # Time tolerance for out-of-order log entries (model level, default: 5s)

    VARIABLE SUBSTITUTION:
    • Use {hostname} in patterns for hostname substitution (default: controller-0)
    • Use {varname} for custom variables defined with --var varname=value
    • Example: "{hostname} Unlock Action" becomes "controller-0 Unlock Action"
    • Variables are substituted before pattern matching occurs

    PATTERN MATCHING RULES:
    • All patterns support full regular expressions (.*+?^$[]{}()|\\ etc.)
    • Pattern blocks: Multiple patterns in a block are processed SEQUENTIALLY
      - Each pattern must be found AFTER the previous pattern in the same block
      - All patterns in a block must be found for the block to succeed
      - Use OR patterns ["option1", "option2"] when you need alternatives
    • Pair blocks: Start pattern must be found before stop pattern
    • Timeline blocks: All patterns searched independently, results sorted chronologically
    • For OR patterns (arrays with [...,...]), first match is used
    • File position tracking ensures chronological ordering
    • Optional blocks show "??:??:??" delta when patterns not found
    • Block type is automatically detected based on 'timeline', 'start'/'stop' vs 'patterns' fields
    • Mixed models process all blocks chronologically regardless of type
    • Timeline patterns have NO order requirements - all matches collected and sorted by timestamp


    MAX_TIME_DELTA CONFIGURATION:
    The max_time_delta setting controls timing constraints for pair blocks and pattern blocks.
    It specifies the maximum allowed time (in seconds) between related events.

    MAX_TIME_DELTA PURPOSE:
    The max_time_delta setting prevents false triggers and maintains
    accurate profile timing for pair and pattern blocks. Without it,
    or with an excessively long value, patterns might match out of context
    (e.g., finding a "stop" pattern from a far into the future) which can
    lead to invalid profile timing from that point forward. This setting
    ensures patterns are found within reasonable time windows relative to
    their context or Warn the user if that block is optional or Error out
    otherwise.

    PRECEDENCE ORDER (highest to lowest):
    1. Block-level max_time_delta: Overrides model level setting for that specific block only
    2. Model settings max_time_delta: Overrides the default for all blocks in the model
    3. Default value: {DEFAULT_MAX_TIME_DELTA} seconds (hardcoded constant DEFAULT_MAX_TIME_DELTA)

    SCOPE AND APPLICATION:
    • Block-level settings apply ONLY to that specific block
    • Model settings apply to ALL blocks in the model (unless overridden at block level)
    • Default applies when no other setting is specified
    • Block-level settings do NOT change the model-wide or default values

    USAGE BY BLOCK TYPE:
    • Pair blocks     : Maximum time between start and stop patterns
    • Pattern blocks  : Maximum time between sequential patterns
                        when explicitly set
    • Timeline blocks : Not applicable. timeline blocks collect all
                        matches regardless of timing.

    EXAMPLES:
    # Model-wide setting affects all pair blocks
    settings:
      max_time_delta: 60  # All pair blocks use 60 seconds unless overridden

    blocks:
      - label: "Fast Service"
        file: "service.log"
        start: "Service starting"
        stop: "Service ready"
        max_time_delta: 10  # This block uses 10 seconds, others use 60

      - label: "Normal Service"
        file: "service.log"
        start: "Normal service starting"
        stop: "Normal service ready"
        # This block uses model setting (60 seconds)

      - label: "Default Service"
        file: "service.log"
        start: "Default service starting"
        stop: "Default service ready"
        # If no model setting exists, uses DEFAULT_MAX_TIME_DELTA ({DEFAULT_MAX_TIME_DELTA} seconds)

    BLOCK_TIME_TOLERANCE CONFIGURATION:
    Controls how far backwards in time the engine will search for the next
    pattern. Handles log entries that are slightly out of chronological order
    due to logging system timing variations, buffering, and write delays.

    Default: 5.0 seconds (model level only)

    PRECEDENCE ORDER (highest to lowest):
    1. Command line --block-time-tolerance: Overrides model settings
    2. Model settings block_time_tolerance: Overrides default
    3. Default value: 5.0 seconds

    USAGE BY BLOCK TYPE:
    * Pattern blocks: Tolerance for sequential pattern matching
    * Pair blocks: Tolerance for start/stop pattern matching
    * Timeline blocks: Not applicable (collect all matches)

    TROUBLESHOOTING:
    * Patterns found out of order: Increase block_time_tolerance
    * False matches occurring: Decrease block_time_tolerance

OUTPUT FORMAT:

    PATTERN BLOCKS:
    Delta(HH:MM:SS)  Block Label       Log File      Data
    ---------------  ---------------   ------------  --------
    00:00:00.000     mtcAgent Unlock   mtcAgent.log  <log line>
